{{Chembox | ImageFile = 3-hydroxydecanoic acid.svg | ImageSize = 200px | ImageAlt = | IUPACName = | OtherNames = 3-Hydroxydecanoic acid; β-Hydroxydecanoic acid; ''beta''-Hydroxydecanoic acid |Section1={{Chembox Identifiers | IUPHAR_ligand = 5848 | CASNo = | PubChem = 26612 | ChEBI_Ref = {{ebicite|correct|EBI}} | ChEBI = 84254 | ChemSpiderID = 132983 | SMILES = CCCCCCCC(CC(=O)O)O | InChI = 1/C10H20O3/c1-2-3-4-5-6-7-9(11)8-10(12)13/h9,11H,2-8H2,1H3,(H,12,13) | InChIKey = FYSSBMZUBSBFJL-UHFFFAOYAJ | StdInChI = 1S/C10H20O3/c1-2-3-4-5-6-7-9(11)8-10(12)13/h9,11H,2-8H2,1H3,(H,12,13) | StdInChIKey = FYSSBMZUBSBFJL-UHFFFAOYSA-N | RTECS = | MeSHName = C017552}} |Section2={{Chembox Properties | C=10 | H=20 | O=3 | Appearance = | Density = | MeltingPt = | BoilingPt = | Solubility = }} |Section3={{Chembox Hazards | MainHazards = | FlashPt = | AutoignitionPt = }} }}
'''Myrmicacin''' ('''3-hydroxydecanoic acid''') is a chemical compound of the β-hydroxycarboxylic acid class. It is named after the South American leaf-cutter ants ([[Myrmicinae]]) in which it was first discovered,<ref name="SchildknechtKoob1971">{{cite journal|last1=Schildknecht|first1=Hermann|last2=Koob|first2=Knut|title=Myrmicacin, The First Insect Herbicide|journal=Angewandte Chemie International Edition in English|volume=10|issue=2|year=1971|pages=124–125|issn=0570-0833|doi=10.1002/anie.197101241}}</ref> but is also found in [[royal jelly]].<ref>{{cite journal|pmid=21082360|year=2011|last1=Kodai|first1=T|last2=Nakatani|first2=T|last3=Noda|first3=N|title=The absolute configurations of hydroxy fatty acids from the royal jelly of honeybees (Apis mellifera)|volume=46|issue=3|pages=263–70|doi=10.1007/s11745-010-3497-x|journal=Lipids}}</ref> Myrmicacin is believed to act as a [[herbicide]] which prevents seeds collected by the ants from germinating within the nest.<ref name="SchildknechtKoob1971"/>
==See also== * [[3,10-Dihydroxydecanoic acid]] * [[3,11-Dihydroxydodecanoic acid]]
