{{refimprove|date=March 2017}}
[[Image:PenetratingFluidCan.jpg|thumb|200px|A 400&nbsp;ml can of penetrating fluid]]
'''Penetrating oil''', also known as '''penetrating fluid''', is very low-[[viscosity]] [[oil]]. It can be used to free rusted mechanical parts (such as nuts and bolts) so that they can be removed, because it can penetrate into the narrow space between the threads of two parts.  It can also be used as a general-purpose [[lubricant]], a cleaner, or a [[corrosion]] stopper. Using penetrating fluids as  general-purpose lubricants is not advisable, because such oils are relatively [[Volatility (chemistry)|volatile]]. As a result, much of the penetrating oil will evaporate in a short amount of time, leaving little residual lubricant.

Other uses include: removing chewing gum and adhesive stickers, lessening friction on metal-stringed musical instruments, various gardening purposes and household repair tasks.

