{{Speciesbox |name = Afrormosia |image = Afrormosia wood(246689720).jpg |image_caption = Afrormosia veneer sample |status = EN |status_system = IUCN2.3 |taxon = Pericopsis elata |authority = (Harms) van Meeuwen |synonyms = * ''Afrormosia elata'' <small>Harms</small> }}
'''''Pericopsis elata''''' is a species of flowering plant in the family ''[[Fabaceae]]'' and is known by the common names '''African teak''', '''afromosia''', '''afrormosia''', '''kokrodua''' and '''assamela'''.<ref name="nils">{{cite journal|last1=Nils|first1=Bourland|last2=Lambert|first2=Kouadio Yao |last3=Philippe |first3=Lejeune |last4=Bonaventure|first4=Sonké|last5=Julien|first5=Philippart|last6=Kasso|first6=Daïnou |last7=Fousséni |first7=Fétéké|last8=Jean-Louis|first8=Doucet|title=Ecology of ''Pericopsis elata'' (Fabaceae), an Endangered Timber Species in Southeastern Cameroon|journal=Biotropica|date=November 2012 |volume=44 |issue=6 |pages=840–847 |doi=10.1111/j.1744-7429.2012.00874.x}}</ref>
==Range== The species is native to moist, semi-deciduous forests in Cameroon, Republic of the Congo, DRC, Ivory Coast, Ghana, and Nigeria.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.iucnredlist.org/species/33191/9759606|title=The IUCN Red List of Threatened Species|website=IUCN Red List of Threatened Species|access-date=2018-10-28}}</ref><ref>[https://www.trada.co.uk/wood-species/afrormosia/ Wood Species Database: Afrormosia - TRADA]</ref>
==Description== The species grows to 30-45m tall with a trunk of 1-1.5m in diameter. Annual diameter increases between unlogged and logged areas have been shown to be similar. It is a deciduous species that flowers at the end of the main dry season. The minimum trunk diameter for reproduction is given as 32&nbsp;cm, while that for effective flowering is 37&nbsp;cm. The fruit take 7 months to mature.<ref name="nils"/>
==Uses== The tree produces hardwood timber of high commercial value due to its texture, strength, density and durability. It is used in the manufacture of boats, veneer and furniture.<ref>[https://www.wood-database.com/afrormosia/ Afrormosia - The Wood Database]</ref>
==Stocks and extraction== The DRC has the world's largest remaining stocks of Afrormosia, which are largely confined to the [[Équateur (former province)|Équateur]] and [[Orientale Province]]s.<ref>Dickson et al. (2005)</ref>
[[Illegal logging]] and [[habitat loss]] pose a realistic threat to the afrormosia, which ranks among the most valued hard tropical timber species.<ref>ITTO (2005)</ref> Following decades of extraction in the 20th and 21st century, it is ranked [[CITES#Appendix II|CITES Appendix II]]. This implies that it is subject to trade regulation because it is recognised that unregulated trade puts the species at risk of extinction. The factors that control its population dynamics are however imperfectly known.<ref name="nils"/> With a minimum logging diameter of 90&nbsp;cm, full recovery is expected over a 30-year period. Selective logging of 12% of seed trees has been shown to have little influence on its survival. Sustainability is believed to be best achieved by purposeful actions to ensure regeneration after logging.<ref name="nils"/>
